<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1929-03-13T03:00:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1929-03-13T03:00:00-05:00" n="572" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d572">
                        <note rend="inline" type="source">711.933/40: Telegram</note>
                        <head><hi rend="italic">The Minister in China</hi> (<persName type="from"><hi rend="italic">MacMurray</hi></persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of State</gloss></hi></head>
                        <opener><dateline rendition="#right"><placeName><hi rend="smallcaps">Peking</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1929-03-13T16:00:00+08:00">March 13, 1929—4
                                p.m.</date><lb/>[Received March 14—10 p.m.]</dateline></opener>
                        <p>173. Reuter carries the following item under date of Nanking, March 12th:
                                <quote rend="blockquote">
                                <p>“Dr. C. T. Wang<note n="46" xml:id="d572fn46">Chinese Minister
                                        for Foreign Affairs.</note> when interviewed informed the
                                    Kuo Min News Agency correspondent that he understands that the
                                    United States Government is exchanging views concerning
                                    abolition of consular jurisdiction with other Governments
                                    concerned, expects that foreign consular jurisdiction will be
                                    abolished before the beginning of next year.”</p>
                            </quote></p>
                        <closer><signed><hi rend="smallcaps">MacMurray</hi></signed></closer>
                    </div>
                    </body></text></TEI>